ing all other entries unchanged","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Unit tests with mock data might pass while real manifest files fail due to parsing edge cases, formatting preservation, and comments. The real failure boundary is when the code must correctly update one dependency in a realistic manifest file without corrupting other entries, preserving whitespace, comments, and format. This requires integration-level testing with actual manifest files and a parser that preserves non-semantic content.","test_description":"Create realistic test manifests (package.json with comments, requirements.txt with comments and line continuations, pyproject.toml with varied formatting) containing multiple dependencies. Modify one dependency's version and verify that only that dependency's version changed. Assert that comments, formatting, order of other dependencies, and any non-version fields remain exactly as they were.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.73,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This requires real git operations (subprocess calls to git), real API calls to create a PR (GitHub/GitLab API), and verification that the diff is correct. Mocking these would hide failures in branch creation, commit message generation, authentication, API integration, and actual diff content. The real failure boundary is the interaction between local git operations, remote API behavior, and repository state. This is inherently a System-level test.","test_description":"Set up a test repository (either a real one or a local git repo). Run the scanner on a manifest with one vulnerable dependency. Verify that a new branch is created with the correct name, a commit is pushed with the correct diff (only one dependency version changed), and a PR is created